81. Search in Rotated Sorted Array II
Problem

An array is sorted in non-decreasing order and then rotated at an unknown pivot.

Unlike Problem 33, duplicate elements are allowed.

Return:

true if the target exists.
false otherwise.
Example
nums = [2,5,6,0,0,1,2]
target = 0

Output: true
Difference Between Problem 33 and Problem 81
Problem 33
[4,5,6,7,0,1,2]

All elements are distinct.

Using:

nums[low] <= nums[mid]

we can always determine which half is sorted.

Problem 81

Duplicates are allowed.

Example:

[1,0,1,1,1]

Suppose:

low = 0
mid = 2
high = 4

Values:

nums[low] = 1
nums[mid] = 1
nums[high] = 1

Now we cannot determine:

Whether the left half is sorted
Whether the right half is sorted

because duplicates hide the pivot.

This is the main challenge of this problem.

Key Observation

In a rotated array:

[4,5,6,7,0,1,2]

At least one half is always sorted.

However, with duplicates:

[1,0,1,1,1]

when:

nums[low] == nums[mid] == nums[high]

we lose the ability to identify the sorted half.

Solution Idea

Before checking which half is sorted:

if(nums[low] == nums[mid] &&
   nums[mid] == nums[high])
{
    low++;
    high--;
}
Why?

Since all three values are identical, they provide no useful information about the pivot.

Therefore, we shrink the search space and continue.

Approach
Step 1

Find the middle element.

int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
Step 2

Check if target is found.

if(nums[mid] == target)
{
    return true;
}
Step 3

Handle duplicates.

if(nums[low] == nums[mid] &&
   nums[mid] == nums[high])
{
    low++;
    high--;
}
Step 4

Determine which half is sorted.

Left Half Sorted
else if(nums[low] <= nums[mid])

Check if target lies inside:

target >= nums[low] &&
target < nums[mid]

If yes:

high = mid - 1;

Otherwise:

low = mid + 1;
Right Half Sorted
else

Check if target lies inside:

target > nums[mid] &&
target <= nums[high]

If yes:

low = mid + 1;

Otherwise:

high = mid - 1;
Code
class Solution {

    public boolean search(int[] nums, int target) {

        int low = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1;

        while(low <= high) {

            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            if(nums[mid] == target) {
                return true;
            }

            // Handle duplicates
            if(nums[low] == nums[mid] &&
               nums[mid] == nums[high]) {

                low++;
                high--;
            }

            // Left half sorted
            else if(nums[low] <= nums[mid]) {

                if(target >= nums[low] &&
                   target < nums[mid]) {

                    high = mid - 1;
                }
                else {
                    low = mid + 1;
                }
            }

            // Right half sorted
            else {

                if(target > nums[mid] &&
                   target <= nums[high]) {

                    low = mid + 1;
                }
                else {
                    high = mid - 1;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}
