Why Do We Use low++ and high--?

Consider:

[1,1,1,1,1]

At:

low = 0
mid = 2
high = 4

All values are equal.

No information can be extracted regarding the pivot.

Therefore:

low++;
high--;

removes duplicate boundaries and helps continue the search.

Complexity Analysis
Average Case

Binary Search behavior:

O(log n)
Worst Case

Example:

[1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1]

Every iteration may only perform:

low++;
high--;

Therefore:

O(n)
Space Complexity
O(1)
Comparison
Problem	Duplicates Allowed	Complexity
33. Search in Rotated Sorted Array	No	O(log n)
81. Search in Rotated Sorted Array II	Yes	O(log n) average, O(n) worst case
Key Takeaway

This problem is almost identical to Problem 33.

The only additional logic is:

if(nums[low] == nums[mid] &&
   nums[mid] == nums[high]) {
    low++;
    high--;
}

This handles the ambiguity caused by duplicate values.

Pattern
1. Check target
2. Handle duplicates
3. Determine sorted half
4. Search in the appropriate half

This is the standard Binary Search pattern for Rotated Sorted Arrays with Duplicates.
